body:
Running circt-opt <file.mlir> -canonicalize with file.mlir having the following content:
```mlir
module {
  hw.module @attrsGone(%arg0: i64, %arg1: i64) -> (out: i32) {
    %2 = comb.mul %arg0, %arg1 {sv.namehint = "test"} : i64
    %3 = comb.extract %2 from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    hw.output %3 : i32
  }
}
```
will loose the `sv.namehint`attribute (and any other custom annotations):
```mlir
module {
  hw.module @attrsGone(%arg0: i64, %arg1: i64) -> (out: i32) {
    %0 = comb.extract %arg0 from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    %1 = comb.extract %arg1 from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    %2 = comb.mul %0, %1 : i32
    hw.output %2 : i32
  }
}
``` 

The issue here is, that `narrowOperationWidth` copies the name to `comb.concat` operation that is created as an immediate step:
 ```mlir
module {
  hw.module @attrsGone(%arg0: i64, %arg1: i64) -> (out: i32) {
    %c0_i32 = hw.constant 0 : i32
    %0 = comb.extract %arg0 from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    %1 = comb.extract %arg1 from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    %2 = comb.mul %0, %1 : i32
    %imm = comb.concat %c0_i32, %2 {sv.namehint = "test"} : i32, i32
    %3 = comb.extract %imm from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    hw.output %2 : i32
  }
} 
 ```
 The sequence of `comb.concat` and `comb.extract` is then optimized away, leaving the narrowed `comb.mul` without any annotations, as shown in the second code snippet.
 
I will submit a PR with a fix for this :)
